'''Marc S. Tucker''' (born 1939) is the president and CEO of the [[National Center on Education and the Economy]]. He is active in [[education reform]] and benchmarking the policies and practices of the countries with the best education systems in the world.

Tucker published a report on international education benchmarking entitled ''Standing on the Shoulders of Giants: An American Agenda for Education Reform''. His book, ''Surpassing Shanghai'', was published by Harvard Education Press in November 2011. According to the publisher, Surpassing Shanghai aims to answer a simple question: How would one redesign the American education system if the aim was to take advantage of everything that has been learned by countries with the world’s best education systems?<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hepg.org/hep/book/142|title=Surpassing Shanghai|author=|date=|website=www.hepg.org|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>  Jay Greene has argued, however, that the "best practice" methodology is flawed and is likely to lead to poor policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://educationnext.org/best-practices-are-the-worst/|title=Best Practices Are the Worst - Education Next|author=|date=3 April 2012|website=educationnext.org|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>

Tucker was influential in creating the [[National Board for Professional Teaching Standards]], the Commission on the Skills of the American Workforce, the New Commission on the Skills of the American Workforce<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skillscommission.org/?p=609+|title=New Commission on The Skills Of The American Workforce Endorses ‘The Opportunity Equation’—Sees Intersection Of Interests Mobilizing For Education Reform  -  NCEE Skills Commission|author=|date=|website=www.skillscommission.org|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>, the New Standards Consortium<ref>http://www.ncrel.org/sdrs/areas/issues/methods/assment/as7nsp.htm%20North%20Central%20Regional%20Educational%20Laboratory</ref>, the National Skills Standards Board, America’s Choice<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americaschoice.org|title=Consulting Services & Personalized Learning - Pearson PD|author=|date=|website=www.americaschoice.org|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref> (a school reform program), the National Institute for School Leadership<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nisl.net/|title=NISL|author=|date=|website=NISL|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>(a school leadership training organization) and Board Examination Systems Program. Tucker has testified to the [[U.S. Congress]] and [[state legislatures]].

He previously served as executive director at Carnegie Forum on Education and the Economy; president at the [[National Board for Professional Teaching Standards]]; associate director at the National Institute of Education, [[U.S. Department of Education]]; and a professor of education at the [[University of Rochester]].{{fact|date=September 2018}}

Tucker was born in [[Newton, Massachusetts]].{{fact|date=September 2018}} He earned a bachelor's degree in philosophy and American literature from [[Brown University]] in 1961.{{fact|date=September 2018}} He subsequently studied theater engineering and technical theater production at the [[Yale School of Drama|Yale University School of Drama]], and then went on to a master of special studies with a concentration in telecommunications policy at [[George Washington University]], graduating in 1982.{{fact|date=September 2018}}

